# App version on git push (`packages/frontend/src/lib/app-version.json`)

The UI version is **A.B.C** (`major`, `minor`, `patch` in JSON):

- **A** — User-controlled release generation; **leave at 3** unless the user explicitly asks to change it.
- **B** — Bump for a **major set of new capabilities** or a broad feature (new flows, integrations, migrations, large cross-cutting work).
- **C** — Bump for **minor fixes** and small, localized changes (tweaks, bugfixes, copy, narrow refactors).

## On every push to git

1. Update `app-version.json` as part of the commit (not a separate drive-by).
2. **Choose B vs C** by judgement: compare the **scope and size** of this change set to what a “minor release” vs “patch” usually means above. It does not need to be perfect.
   - Mostly small fixes / one area → increment **C** only (e.g. 3.12.0 → 3.12.1).
   - Notable new behavior or multi-area feature work → increment **B** and set **C** to **0** (e.g. 3.12.3 → 3.13.0).
3. Do not bump **A** unless the user asks.

This replaces any older rule that always bumped B on every push.
